Dinamics of travel prices since 1989
By 1989, only five public tourist agencies could work in Czechoslovakia: Chadok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autoturist.
Since travels to the West were strictly limited, tourist agencies of that time were mainly selling tours to the countries of the socialist bloc.
Thus, the Czech tourists traveled to the German Democratic Republic; the Soviet Union (Soci, Crime in the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (both countries in the Black Sea); and Hungary (Balaton).
The only exception was the period from 1962 to 1972 when we had the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia, and then the Yugoslav regime returned to the West, which led to significant restrictions on the visits of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia.
The great paradox of the socialist period was that civilians of the Socialist bloc (i.e. and Czechoslovakia) were not allowed to travel individually to socialist countries.
If the Czech Slovakia citizen wanted to go to the Soviet Union or Poland, a invitation from that country was needed; otherwise, it was not possible to travel individually.
At that time, tourist agencies offered travel to the West, but they had to either stand in a row all night with a bedroom bag or have "good friends" in the agency.
And that was not all.
The currency permit was required to travel to the West and was not issued to politically unreliable people who were not allowed to travel.
The Czech Slovak currency was not freely converted; without currency, money (west currency) could not be obtained to travel to the West.
The Czech Republic has often conducted their holidays at home, which has led to a large number of houses and summer houses, and this habit remains to this day.
Since 1989, tourism in Czech Republic thus survived this revolution.
While until 1989 the leave to GDR or Bulgaria was a culmination of our travel, the Czech Republic held 4.5 million vacations throughout the world last year.
The great paradox, which we no longer realize, is that until 1989, we could not freely visit the most popular Croatia, as it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
In the beginning of 1990, the need for visa in neighbouring countries of Western Europe was cancelled, which has led to a huge wave of short travel mainly to Vienna and Germany.
The Czech Slovakia could not find a lot of journeys to the West, and everyone wanted to go there for a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists had been sleeping in tents in the parks, since their income was not enough for a hotel or a pension at the time.
The typical feature of Czech tourism during that period was the desire to bring its own food (conservations, salads, etc.) to save money.
Another important moment is the introduction of a freely converted Czech crown, and after decades, our tourists can finally buy the west currency freely.
Our life level and average income grew, which led to another important situation in 1997.
Since 1997, the increased demand has allowed tourism agencies to prepare regular flights carried out by charter airlines.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs did not need a visa to visit almost all developed world countries except the United States, which made our trips even easier.
The next significant event in the history of travels after the revolution took place in 2000, and the great demand led to the historically first direct charter flight from the Czech Republic to the exotic country, Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights have delivered Czech tourists to warm exotic countries, and this winter flights from the Czech Republic will be sent to the twelve exotic directions.
At present, about 100,000 Czech countries visit exotic countries every year!
And another important event of this period, which symbolizes our development after the revolution, happened in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the United States renounced the need for a visa for Czech tourists, thus joining the most developed world countries forever.
For the first time in history in 2008, more than half of their vacations spent abroad (50.3 per cent); and for the first time in history they spent over 15,000 crowns per person during abroad leave, including their expenditures in the appointment.
